  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Three Times the Refusal Was Not Accepted
  author: Choi Yu-cheong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A prime minister stands in the inner halls because we honor the weight of debating the Way; the three dukes must be men of true worth because we illuminate the esteem we place on selecting the virtuous. So if one can truly bear the mandate of all-under-heaven without doubt, then great office brings no hesitation.

    You rose long ago from the Bureau of Secretaries to the seat of Deputy Prime Minister, walking steadfast in virtue and becoming the model for ten thousand people. Though dwelling in wealth and rank, your heart has never clung to them; though meeting the moment to build your legacy, you have remained untouched by its snare. This is why I offer my trust with an open heart, and why the people all look to you to grasp the helm of state.

    Yet why do you cling so stubbornly to modesty, declining again and again each commendation? Once, Fang Xuanling and Du Ruhui worked as one, and the Tang Emperor relied upon their strength to accomplish great things. And when Shun and Gao Tao each deferred to the other, the Sage Emperor would not permit their request.

    My resolve was settled long before—no flood of words shall sway it. You must serve not with further letters of refusal that bind you to your reluctance, but with the substance of our shared purpose. Accept this command already given, and move with the voice of all.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Fang Xuanling (房玄齡) and Du Ruhui (杜如晦) were renowned ministers under Tang Taizong, exemplifying harmonious collaboration in governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Shun and Gao Tao alludes to legendary sage-rulers who sought wise counselors despite their modesty.
